            </span-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>When Randy was a little over two years old he was injured by a gunshot wound to the jaw, by a 22 bullet that entered his right jaw and traveled upwards towards his ear, where it left the jaw. Randy and Debra were in the pickup when it happened and were with their Dad who was taking them with him to the mill in Ririe. They were in the pickup alone when they discovered the gun behind the seat and began to investigate. Apparently Debra had seen someone eject a shell from a gun before and she tried to do the same thing when the gun discharged into Randy’s jaw. 


            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                    
                </ol>    
            </div-->


            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    When Ken came out of the mill, Randy was bleeding very heavily and he hurried to Rigby to the doctor there but could not get any help at all, so after calling Aunt Mary and having her get in touch with me to meet him in Rigby we drove like crazy to Dr. Reed Fife’s office in Idaho Falls. Dr. Fife told us then that Randy had a gunshot wound and we took him to the hospital immediately. The bullet had entered through the lower jaw and traveled on an angle upward through the jaw, toward the ear where it exited without injuring the ear. His little jaw was shattered and resulted in a long and tedious series of surgery and orthodontia. <br /><br />

                    While Randy was in the hospital one of the nurses neglected to raise the sidebar on his crib-bed and he tumbled out onto the floor but sustained no further injury. The first time in the hospital was for two weeks and he was a very sick little boy. We were blessed that the injury had not resulted in any facial distortion but a severe malocclusion of his jaws and teeth, which we would discover later would be with him for the rest of his life. He spent many years under Dr. Thompson’s care and had surgery in Boise several times. Dr. Fife also followed his care and contributed much to Randy’s progress.
            </span>
            
            <!--span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory1-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory1');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory1" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    When I met Ken and came to love him, my desire for a temple marriage increased, and my testimony became stronger, as well as my desire to always be part of the Church and the gospel, and have the gospel as the centermost part of our marriage, and to raise our children so they would be faithful and active so they could develop their own testimonies. <br /><br />

                    When Kenneth and I were called very unexpectedly to serve a mission in the Guatemala City Mission and accepted that call, we served for eighteen months. During the first few weeks there I began to read the Book of Mormon fully. Now that I recall, I don’t think I had ever read that book from cover to cover until that time. When I came to read the last page, a feeling came over me I had not experienced before. The tears came unexpectedly, and I knew then without a doubt that the book was true, and indeed that Christ is the Savior. It’s a feeling I shall never forget.  <br /><br />

                    When Ken and I began our family, one thing we were sure that we wanted was for our sons serve as missionaries. Our desire for this was really strong. I could hardly wait to have a missionary in our family. Mike was nineteen when he chose to serve, and I remember being so excited that when his call came, I ripped open the envelope and read where he would go, and then I went to find him at his work to tell him he was called to the New Zealand Mission. These days moms do not, I repeat, do not open any person’s mission envelope! <br /><br />

                    Marlon was called to the Indonesia Mission. Robert followed and served in Australia. Randy’s call was to Oakland, and we worried more about him being in Oakland than the other three boys being 8,000 miles away. Two very special bonuses have been having our two daughters also serve: Debra in the Italy Rome Mission, and Janet in the Peru Mission.  <br /><br />

                    Janet…that’s a little special experience there as well, because when we were called by Bishop Parkinson, we were totally in shock. We had no clue that he was going to call us. So we called our family and told everyone, and when we told Janet, she said, “They can’t do that! The Church can’t do that! I’m not married yet. You can’t go leave me. I’m coming home this next weekend.” She was going to school at BYU. So she came home and made an appointment with the bishop, and he called her to serve a mission. She was 21 and served in the Peru Mission. We were blessed to serve with her in the MTC for three weeks of our time down there. We were all three learning Spanish, and it was a wonderful time together.  <br /><br />

                    It seems that we have been blessed to be a missionary family, having all of our children serve, and then Ken and I being blessed to serve together for three missions, and then after Ken left, I was blessed to serve again.  <br /><br />

                    My patriarchal blessing promises me that if I will be true and faithful to my covenants and set a proper example, my children will honor and revere my name throughout eternity. This has been my heart’s desire above everything. Now many of the grandchildren have served as well, and missionary service has been a real blessing in our family. It has been a great blessing in choices of spouses, as well, that our children have made. We truly as a family have loved missionary service, and that has been a tremendous factor in the strengthening of my testimony and the gratitude I feel to the Lord for the blessings he has given to me and to my family.
                </span-->

