            </span-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>Our years at the farm were happy years. We lived in Milo for 16 years. All six of our children were born while we lived on the farm. We had wonderful, happy years at the farm but also had some adversity mixed in with the happy. But looking back at the adversity somehow seems to strengthen the faith we had in the Lord and keep us close and supportive and loving to one another. 
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                   
                    
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                Michael was desperately ill when he contracted, we knew not how, a disease called Stevens-Johnson syndrome. By all known prognosis of that disease, he should not have survived, but he did and we knew then that the Lord had much in mind for Mike not to have taken him through all that. Mike also had a “to do” with a mother cow who had recently produced a beautiful calf that Mike got a little too playful with and the mom bunted him and seriously injured him so that surgery was required. Robert had a broken leg while contending with a post hole digger. 


            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Mike and Marlon also had quite an episode of ringworm on their legs as a result of them riding a cow around in the corral, Mike was especially sick as a result of that adventure. The mom of the family, me, contracted a strep infection that resulted in rheumatic fever and required bed rest for several months. I had to leave the farm and family to rest at Grandma Ingram’s for several months, while the family fended for themselves. Working together and depending on others for support were what kept us going. <br /><br />

                    After 16 years farming and because of Ken's looming, possibly serious back problems, we decided to sell the farm and endeavor to find another way to provide for us all. We also could see that if we chose to stay and continue farming, we would be required to invest in bigger and more modern equipment and machinery, which would require investing much money to do so. We chose not to go that way as we had no debt and wanted to remain so if possible, so decided that the farm must go. 
 
                </span>

