        <div id="ChapterText" class="clearfix">
            <!--span id="ChapterByline">
            <span id="textspanlichapter22">ALICE CHAU</span><br /><span id="textspanlichapter24">SISTER</span>
            </span-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>In between chores and church work and the farm work, I had a sore throat that persisted and would not leave me. I remember that I noticed it was quite chronic at the time that I was canning cherries and was quite sick with the sore throat. I didn't pay too much attention to it because sore throats had always been quite common with me so I went about with my work and tried to ignore it, which, it turned out to be, was very foolish and had I gone to a doctor for an antibiotic I would have saved a lot of trauma for myself and entire family during t at summer. We as a family had planned a fishing and camping trip to Yellowstone and after the work was caught up we did go right on with the trip even though I felt quite sick. 


            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                        
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                We borrowed Larene’s big white tent and loaded it with all of our camping equipment and food and we stayed for three days and the kids seemed to have fun despite the fact that their mother was very, very ill. When we returned home, I discovered that there was a constant fever, and my legs were swelling and beginning to break out In a rash. I also had a nasty rash on my neck and was so ill that we went to Dr. Baker the next day and the tests showed that I either had Rheumatic Fever or Lupus. 
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory3-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory3');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory3" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Well, my nursing background helped me to remember that Lupus was a very serious disease, most often fatal within possibly two or three years so that caused me to have many sleepless nights until the tests proved that it was indeed Rheumatic Fever. My mother was alone there in Idaho Falls and we all felt that because of the complete bedrest that was necessary for my recovery that it would be best for me to stay with her for as long as possible that summer so that is what we did. I was back in my bedroom at home with my wonderful mother carrying for me. <br /><br />

                    But, at the farm, there was my husband with a 160 acre farm, a herd of milk cows and pigs etc. the middle of summer when there is so much work to do…irrigating…and with six young children to care for! Well, with the help of good family and friends we managed to get through it all. The children really pitched in and helped; certain responsibilities were delegated and they all did the best they could. Janet was only three years old so she was shifted from relative to relative and at times protested quite loudly about her circumstances. <br /><br />

                    Grandma Ingram managed the best she could with her at times but it was difficult for her to tend a three year old and a patient at the same time. I am not sure what or how the chores were delegated at the farm but with the help of Relief Society; and neighbors they managed pretty well. Marlon was the chief cook and I remember the day I came home from Mother's to finish recuperating at home that he had baked a beautiful chocolate cake for the family and it was delicious. Now it is all memory but I had very good care and unlike most Rheumatic Fever patients I recuperated without any complications whatsoever and all that was required for me to continue to do was get plenty of rest and take Penicillin tablets every day for a number of years. Again, as my patriarchal blessing had promised: health of body.
                </span>

