            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>In 1978 it became necessary for me to undergo surgery and this was to be done at Madison Memorial Hospital, which was located about 1/2 block from where we lived on Reed Street. We could see part of the hospital building from our front yard. From my room in the hospital, I could look out and see part of our home. Two or three days after surgery, I could hear a fire truck with its loud siren and it seemed very close. I climbed out of bed to look out the window and saw that the engine did not continue on Reed Street, but it looked as it stopped in front of my house! And sure enough it stopped there. 
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                        
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                My first thoughts were, “What is happening? Is there a fire at my house or elsewhere in the neighborhood?” Panic began to consume my thoughts and got more intense as each minute passed. Before long, Ken arrived and informed me that yes, there was a fire in our home downstairs in the family room and it was completely gutted out and it smoked all through the house. He said the fire started when a burning log fell from the fireplace and started the carpet on fire and spread to a couch and then on to consume the entire room. No one was at home.
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory4-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory4');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory4" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Ken said he was going back to work at the drive-in and before leaving the house put a log on the fire and then left. In a few moments the burning log rolled out and onto the floor and because there was no screen on the fire base to stop the log, it rolled on and started the room and everything in it to be destroyed. <br /><br />

                    He came into my hospital room to tell me the sad news with a heavy heart. Apparently, the company that installed the fireplace were responsible to include a safety screen but failed to do so. Had that been done correctly the log would not have rolled out of the fireplace. Sad news.
                </span>

